200 Section 3. Sections 37-1-81.1 and 31-1-81.2 are added
201 to the Code of Alabama 1975 to read as follows:
202 §37-1-81.1
203 (a) The retail base rates established and in place on
204 October 1, 2026 for each utility that is regulated by the
205 commission and that provides retail electric service may not
206 be increased before June 1, 2029.
207 (b) On and after June 1, 2029, a utility that provides
208 retail electric service may not factor the following costs
209 into the calculation or determination of a new rate or service
210 regulation or a change to an existing rate or service
211 regulation charged to customers of the utility:
212 (1) Costs incurred due to the utility providing funding
213 or grants that impact rates to other persons or organizations.
214 (2) Costs incurred due to the hiring of persons for the
215 purpose of lobbying the Legislature or any other political
216 office or subdivision of the state.
217 (3) Costs incurred due to advertisement of the utility
218 other than public safety advertising approved by the
219 commission.
220 (c)(1) When an electric utility files a new schedule to
221 put in operation a new rate or service regulation or to change
222 an existing rate or service regulation, the utility shall
223 affirm that the utility has not included the prohibited costs
224 under subsection (b) in the calculation or determination of
Page 8

under subsection (b) in the calculation or determination of
SB360 INTRODUCED
225 the rate or service regulation.
226 (2) If the electric utility fails to make the
227 affirmation, the rate or service regulation shall be void.
228 (d) If the commission discovers that a utility has
229 included the prohibited cost under subsection (b) in the
230 calculation or determination of rates or service regulations,
231 the commission shall investigate the determination pursuant to
232 Section 37-1-83 and other powers of investigation granted to
233 the commission pursuant to this division.
234 §37-1-81.2
235 The commissioners and staff of the commission shall
236 convene at least one public meeting per calendar year with
237 utility representatives to provide information to the public
238 on cost trends, reliability, resilience, general
239 infrastructure investment plans, economic development impacts,
240 security of the power grid, national trends in energy
241 production, and other regulatory issues the Secretary of
242 Energy deems relevant. The public meetings shall be conducted
243 in a manner that gives residents the opportunity to
244 participate, addresses concerns voiced by the public, and
245 provides a review of key issues that the secretary believes
246 will be helpful to the public in understanding issues that
247 impact services under its jurisdiction.
